ersity of Birmingham\">University of Birmingham<\/a>. He received the 1937 <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Chemistry\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Chemistry\">Nobel Prize in Chemistry<\/a> \"for his investigations on <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Carbohydrate\" title=\"Carbohydrate\">carbohydrates<\/a> and vitamin C\". The prize was shared with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Switzerland\" title=\"Switzerland\">Swiss<\/a> chemist <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Paul_Karrer\" title=\"Paul Karrer\">Paul Karrer<\/a> for his work on other <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Vitamin\" title=\"Vitamin\">vitamins<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Norman_Haworth#cite_note-3\"><span>[<\/span>3<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Norman_Haworth#cite_note-4\"><span>[<\/span>4<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>Haworth worked out the correct structure of a number of sugars, and is known among organic chemists for his development of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Haworth_projection\" title=\"Haworth projection\">Haworth projection<\/a> that translates three-dimensional sugar structures into convenient two-dimensional graphical form.<\/p>","name":"Norman Haworth","place_of_birth":"90 Park Road,  Chorley ,  Lancashire ,  England","place_of_death":"Barnt Green ,  Worcestershire ,  England","text":"Norman Haworth , Chemistry, 1937","year":1937.0}